        "explanation": "<strong>Evaluating Logical Claims:</strong><br>• <strong>(A) False:</strong> Immediate inference relies on exactly ONE premise, not more than one (which is mediate inference/syllogism).<br>• <strong>(B) True:</strong> Contradictory propositions (like A and O, or E and I) are exact denials of each other.<br>• <strong>(C) False:</strong> Sub-contraries (I and O) <em>can</em> both be true, but they <em>cannot</em> both be false. The statement has it backward.<br>• <strong>(D) True:</strong> All negative propositions (E and O) always distribute their predicate term.<br>• <strong>(E) False:</strong> Quantity (Universal/Particular) determines subject distribution. Quality (Affirmative/Negative) determines predicate distribution.<br>Therefore, B and D are the correct claims."
